**Subnet Update**

@ready・33 We are pushing back the closure of the Conversation Server to non-validators to this upcoming Monday, October 14th at 12pm PST. Here are some more details of how this will go down:

**Mainnet:**
 
 * Beginning Monday, we will be enforcing a weights_version hyperparameter. This will require all validators to have a specified version of the repository in order to set weights. 
 * Prior to setting this hyperparameter, we will release an update that prevents validators from setting weights unless they receive a conversation from an API endpoint and query miners - preventing hung validators from setting outdated weights.
 * The weights_version hyperparameter will subsequently be set to the spec version for the release described above.
 * After the updates described above, we will lockdown the API endpoint on our side to only permit validators to access the API

In effect, this will provide 2 major improvements to the subnet: 
 
 * Preventing hung validators from setting outdated weights if they are experiencing problems or errors with their operations, or if they have outdated scoring mechanisms due to future subnet updates
 * Preventing non-validators from accessing the Conversations Server and developing lookup attack methods.

**Testnet:**

As part of our conversations server updates, we will be providing a specific, isolated subset of conversations for testnet operations. Beginning on Monday, Validators with a testnet -compatible API key will be able to query the Conversations Server to receive conversations from this subset. Any Testnet validator with minimum 10tao staked will be able to get a testnet API key. For instructions on how to do this, please see the documentation in docs/generate-validator-api-key.md

**New Release Live - ReadyAI 2.6.28**

@ready・33 We just pushed out a new release to the main branch **for both Validators & Miners** with the following updates:
 * Increase miners per window 
  * Currently, building incentive as a miner takes ~24 hours. By increasing miners per window from 3->6, incentive can be built much quicker, and neurons are much more resilient to outdate/erroneous scores should a validator have an outage or load an outdated state
 * Eliminate Miner Embedding Generation
  * Miners no longer generate embeddings for their tags. Since Version 1.91.14, Validators have been ignoring miner-generated embeddings and generating on their own to prevent dishonest miner activity. Now, miners will no longer generating the embeddings altogether.
  * This should present a meaningful increase to subnet speed and throughput, and decrease miner costs. 

Both of these updates are intended to increase the speed and resiliency of building miner incentive. We have listened to the community and their problems over the last month, and we believe that this is a big step in the right direction. 

To supplement this push, we will be implementing a state check system that will ensure that new or outdated validators do not load a state that is out of consensus. This will curb any impacts that unexpected technical outages or new validator registration has on building miner incentive. Expect this early next week. 

We will be messaging validators to update, however we will not update the weights_version until Monday, November 4th at 12pm PST. Between now and then, updated validators will build scores for new miners at a faster pace than outdated validators, however we do not expect any other impacts from this update, therefore we will not be closing registration.

Thank you all and please feel free to reach out for any questions.

I’ve been trying to raise concerns about the closed API, and while the article makes some bold claims, I think many would agree that the current structure has significant flaws. With the closed API, several potential issues could arise (though I’m not suggesting they currently do):  

- **ReadyAI** could engage in mining themselves, as they control what is sent to validators. While there’s no evidence this is happening, the possibility exists.  
- **Validators** might collect data to refine or test their own approaches.  
- **Miners** holding more than 1/6th of the total nodes (since each datapoint is sent to 6 miners) could capture over 99% of the conversations, potentially giving them an unfair advantage. While this issue is mentioned in the article, I want to focus on other aspects.  

In my view, the only viable solution is for validators to scrape data directly from the source themselves or for the dataset to be made entirely open source. Such a dataset would need to be either augmented (like SN32 / SN34) or so large that hashing it becomes impractical (like SN32). While splitting conversation windows, as suggested in the article, might address the issue of increasing scores, it doesn’t solve the underlying structural problems.  

I understand that OTF required the API to be closed to prevent the dataset from being scraped and hashed. However, this decision has introduced new inequities, creating potential advantages for both validators and ReadyAI.
